Conditioning on survival
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the limit, the probability for extinction is given by the smallest positive
 root of 
\begin_inset Formula $q=f(q)$
\end_inset

.
 We can define a new process with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{\star}(s)=\frac{f\left[\left(1-q\right)s+q\right]-q}{1-q}
\]

\end_inset

which will yield the a limit distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\star}(W)=(1-q)H(W)+q\delta(W)$
\end_inset

.
 Note in particular that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\star}$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of the same order as 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:forward-examples"

\end_inset

Examples of limiting distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we consider a simple binary fission 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s)=s^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributed cell cycles
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(t)=\frac{\beta^{\beta}t^{\beta-1}e^{-\beta t}}{\Gamma(\beta)}.
\]

\end_inset

The limiting distributions (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:g-gamma-limits"

\end_inset

) are remarkably close to being 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributed also, but not quite (inset).
 As we show in appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "app:examples"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

-distributions are legitimate limiting distributions, but to a slightly
 different cell cycle distribution.
\end_layout

