where the summation runs over all partitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}+2k_{2}+\cdots+nk_{n}=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=k_{1}+\cdots+k_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Recognising these as moments (up to factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 which may be removed without loss of generality by picking the right boundary
 conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

) gives (using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}=\phi(0)=1$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{n}=\sum_{\mathbf{k}}\frac{n!}{k_{1}!\cdots k_{n}!}f^{(k)}\left(1\right)\left(\frac{M_{1}}{1!}\right)^{k_{1}}\cdots\left(\frac{M_{n}}{n!}\right)^{k_{n}}\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy.\label{eq:moment-recursion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we assumed that all moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 exist, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{(k)}(1)$
\end_inset

 will also exist.
 Noticing that there is only one partition with 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}=1$
\end_inset

, we can move that term to the left hand side and we get for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge2$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{n}\left[1-\int_{0}^{\infty}f^{\prime}(1)e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy\right]=C\left[M_{1},\ldots,M_{n-1}\right],
\]

\end_inset

where the right hand side only depends on the lower moments, and in particular
 is finite if all the lower moments are finite.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\int_{0}^{\infty}f^{\prime}(1)e^{-y}g(y)\, dy<\int_{0}^{\infty}f^{\prime}(1)e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy
\]

\end_inset

and since 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 is finite, by induction all moments exist.
 Thus, applying Chebychev's inequality we get 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)\in o\left(W^{-\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 We conjecture that it is actually exponentially bounded, and show this
 below for binary fission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now outline a plausible argument that the tails are also bounded from
 below by an exponential.
 Although we do not have proofs, it seems reasonable that some morally similar
 statements must be true.
 First, it seems plausible that if two non-negative variables 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}$
\end_inset

 with unity mean, have moments obeying
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[W_{1}^{n}\right]\ge\mathbb{E}\left[W_{2}^{n}\right]
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w>w_{0}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}\left[W_{1}>w\right]>\mathbb{P}\left[W_{2}>w\right].
\]

\end_inset

 Second, if the moments 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\mathbb{E}\left[W^{n}\right]\in n\log n+\Theta(n)$
\end_inset

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 then the tail 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[W>w\right]$
\end_inset

 is exponential, in some sense.
 In particular, previous work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Abate1996"

\end_inset

 suggests that if the limits 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{n}=\frac{n\mathbb{E}\left[W^{n-1}\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[W^{n}\right]}\rightarrow\eta
\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{n}=\frac{\eta_{n}^{n}\mathbb{E}\left[W^{n}\right]}{n!}\rightarrow A
\]

\end_inset

 exist, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{w\rightarrow\infty}e^{\eta w}\mathbb{P}\left[W>w\right]=A.
\]

\end_inset

 Finally, we consider equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:moment-recursion"

\end_inset

 and drop all terms higher than quadratic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{M_{n}}{n!}\ge\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}\frac{M_{k}M_{n-k}}{k!(n-k)!}\frac{f^{\prime\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy}{1-f^{\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy}\label{eq:moments-lower-bound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which follows as each term in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:moment-recursion"

\end_inset

 is positive.
 We can think of this as a new branching process for which that recurrence
 relation is exact, which corresponds to a binary fission process with possible
 death.
 That process has moments 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}^{\star}=n!\xi(n)$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi(n)=\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}\xi(k)\xi(n-k)\frac{f^{\prime\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy}{1-f^{\prime}(1)\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy}.
\]

\end_inset

 Asymptotically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-ny}g(y)\, dy\in\Omega\left(e^{-cn}\right)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is bounded from below by an exponential.
 Thus, we conclude that the process with moments 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 has an exponential tail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of binary fission, we can improve the upper bound slightly.
 In particular, the equality in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:moments-lower-bound"

\end_inset

 applies.
 An upper bound on the moments is then given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{K_{2}M_{n}}{n!}\le\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}\frac{K_{2}M_{k}}{k!}\frac{K_{2}M_{n-k}}{(n-k)!}.
\]

\end_inset

with equality for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\le2$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{2}=\frac{2\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-2y}g(y)\, dy}{1-2\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-2y}g(y)\, dy}.
\]

\end_inset

We obtain an upper bound in terms of the Catalan numbers
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{K_{2}M_{n}}{n!}\le\frac{K_{2}^{n}(2n-2)!}{(n-1)!n!}
\]

\end_inset

Then applying the moments bound
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Philips1995"

\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}\left[W>w\right]=\inf_{n}\frac{M_{n}}{w^{n}}\le\inf_{n}\frac{K_{2}^{n-1}(2n-2)!}{(n-1)!w^{n}},
\]

\end_inset

which for large 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{P}\left[W>w\right]=O\left(\frac{1}{w}\right)e^{-\frac{w}{4K_{2}}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we note that removing the assumption that all moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 exist will remove the upper bound but not the exponential lower bound.
 Furthermore, if the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is infinite, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th moment of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 will be as well, suggesting a tail 
\begin_inset Formula $H(W)\approx W^{-k-1}$
\end_inset

; indeed, the moment will diverge at finite times.
\end_layout

